Applebaum has written extensively on the Ukraine conflict, arguing in her book *Autocracy, Inc.* and in columns for *The Atlantic* that Russian aggression stems from a global trend toward authoritarianism. Her work has been praised for its historical depth and clarity, but has also drawn criticism from some scholars and journalists. Critics have accused Applebaum of oversimplifying the conflict by framing it primarily as a struggle between democracy and autocracy, thereby downplaying geopolitical factors such as NATO expansion and Ukraine's internal political dynamics.<ref>{{cite news |last=Koval |first=Andriy |date=2023-03-15 |title=The Limits of the 'Autocracy vs. Democracy' Frame |url=https://jacobin.com/2023/03/applebaum-ukraine-autocracy-democracy-critique |work=Jacobin |access-date=2025-01-20}}</ref> Additionally, some commentators have identified an ideological bias in her work, arguing that her narrative aligns too closely with a Western liberal interventionist perspective, which can obscure the role of economic interests and historical grievances in the conflict.<ref>{{cite news |last=Walt |first=Stephen M. |date=2022-09-12 |title=The Ukraine War Is Not a Simple Morality Play |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2022/09/12/ukraine-war-morality-play-applebaum/ |work=Foreign Policy |access-date=2025-01-20}}</ref> These critiques suggest that while Applebaum's analysis is influential, it may not fully capture the complexity of the war's origins and the range of scholarly interpretations.

